Project Objective¶

  • Apply torque on the free end to swing it into an upright position.

Questions¶

  • how to systematically optimise your solutions
  • What hyperparameters can you tune?
  • How many trials does it need?
  • How do you conclusively demonstrate your so-called “best setup” to be the best?
  • What is criteria to use (fastest learning | most stable learning | others)

Background¶

Training an AI to balance a pendulum, known as the inverted pendulum problem, serves as a foundational challenge in control theory and reinforcement learning with broad practical applications.

The principles and techniques developed for this task are critical in robotics, such as for self-balancing robots and robotic manipulators, as well as in aerospace engineering for stabilizing rockets and maintaining satellite orientation. Additionally, these concepts are applied in transportation systems, including self-driving cars and motorcycles, and in active suspension systems for vehicles to enhance stability and safety.

Beyond these areas, the balancing algorithms are also utilized in renewable energy systems, like optimizing wind turbine control and stabilizing wave energy converters. In healthcare, they contribute to the development of advanced prosthetics and rehabilitation robotics, improving patient support and mobility. Moreover, entertainment and gaming industries leverage these techniques for creating more immersive virtual and augmented reality experiences, while camera gimbals use them to ensure smooth footage in dynamic conditions. These diverse applications showcase the far-reaching impact of mastering the balancing challenge in AI and control systems.

Gym Info¶

The inverted pendulum swingup problem is based on the classic problem in control theory. The system consists of a pendulum attached at one end to a fixed point, and the other end being free. The pendulum starts in a random position and the goal is to apply torque on the free end to swing it into an upright position, with its center of gravity right above the fixed point.


  • x-y: cartesian coordinates of the pendulum’s end in meters.
  • theta : angle in radians.
  • tau: torque in N m. Defined as positive counter-clockwise.

Observation Space¶

Observation Min Max
x = cos(theta) -1.0 1.0
y = sin(angle) -1.0 1.0
Angular Velocity -8.0 8.0

Continuous Actions¶

Action Min Max
Torque -2.0 2.0

Rewards¶

  • $r = -(theta2 + 0.1 * theta_dt2 + 0.001 * torque2)$

Starting State¶

  • The starting state is a random angle in [-$π$, $π$] and a random angular velocity in [-1,1].

def analyze_rewards(env, num_episodes=100):
    rewards = []
    for _ in range(num_episodes):
        state = env.reset()
        episode_reward = 0
        for _ in range(200):  # Limit the length of each episode
            action = env.action_space.sample()
            next_state, reward, done, _ = env.step(action)
            episode_reward += reward
            if done:
                break
        rewards.append(episode_reward)
    return rewards

rewards = analyze_rewards(env)
sns.histplot(rewards, bins=20, kde=True)
plt.xlabel("Total Reward")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.title("Distribution of Total Rewards for Random Actions")
plt.show()

Observation:

  • There isn't a visible trend of the score.

The best possible score would theoretically be 0 because 0 is the lowest possible reward. This is wildly improbable, though, as it would take a tremendous amount of luck for the pendulum to be always oriented with an angle of zero

def sample_states(env, num_samples=1000):
    states = []
    for _ in range(num_samples):
        state = env.reset()
        states.append(state)
    return np.array(states)

states = sample_states(env)
sns.pairplot(pd.DataFrame(states, columns=["cos(theta)", "sin(theta)", "theta_dot"]))
plt.suptitle("Distribution of Initial States", y=1.02)
plt.show()

Observation¶

  • Initial State Distribution:
    • cos(theta) and sin(theta): These form a perfect circle when plotted against each other, indicating that the initial angle is uniformly distributed across all possible angles (0 to 2π radians or 0 to 360 degrees).
    • theta_dot: The angular velocity seems to be initialized with a uniform distribution between approximately -1 and 1, suggesting the pendulum can start with any speed within this range, in either direction.
  • Independence:
    • The scatter plots between theta_dot and cos(theta) or sin(theta) show a uniform rectangular distribution, indicating that the initial angle and angular velocity are independently sampled.
  • Constraints:
    • The cos(theta) and sin(theta) values are constrained between -1 and 1, as expected for trigonometric functions.
    • theta_dot appears to be constrained between approximately -1 and 1, suggesting a maximum initial angular velocity in either direction.

Model Training¶

Types of Architecture¶

  • Value-based methods:

These algorithms focus on learning the value function, which estimates the expected return from a state or state-action pair.
DQN and NoisyDQN fall into this category as they both aim to approximate the Q-value function. - DQN (Deep Q-Network) - NoisyDQN

  • Policy-based methods:

These algorithms directly optimize the policy without necessarily learning a value function.
PPO is a policy-based method that uses trust region optimization to improve the policy. - PPO (Proximal Policy Optimization)

  • Actor-Critic methods:

These algorithms combine elements of both value-based and policy-based approaches.
They typically have two components: an "actor" that learns the policy and a "critic" that learns the value function.
Both SAC and DDPG are actor-critic methods. - SAC (Soft Actor-Critic) - DDPG (Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient)

However, we will only be eploring the DQN, NoisyDQN & DDPG

HyperParameters¶

  • *Network Architecture Parameters*

    • Intermediate Size
      • Description: The size of the intermediate layers in the neural network.
      • Purpose: Specifies the number of neurons in the hidden layers of the neural network, affecting the capacity and performance of the model.

  • *Training Parameters*

    • Learning Rate
      • Description: The learning rate for the network.
      • Purpose: Controls how much the network's weights are adjusted with respect to the gradient during training.
    • Gamma
      • Description: The discount factor for future rewards.
      • Purpose: Determines the importance of future rewards compared to immediate rewards. A value closer to 1 makes the agent consider long-term rewards more.
    • Batch Size
      • Description: The number of samples used in one training iteration.
      • Purpose: Defines how many experiences are drawn from the replay memory to compute the gradient, impacting the stability and speed of learning.
    • Replay_memory Size
      • Description: The maximum size of the replay memory.
      • Purpose: Limits the number of past experiences stored for training the agent. Larger sizes can provide more diverse training data.
    • Min Replay Memory Size
      • Description: The minimum size of replay memory before training starts.
      • Purpose: Ensures that a sufficient amount of experiences is available in the replay memory to sample from, which helps in stabilizing training.

Leanring Process (Graphs)¶

  • Average Q-value Over Step: Represents the estimated value of actions.
  • Episode Return Over Time: Shows the total reward obtained in each episode.
  • Gradient Over Step: Shows how much the model's parameters are changing at each step.
  • Loss Over Step: Indicates the error in the model's predictions.

Common Functions¶

In [ ]:
def PendulumActionConverter(A, NActions=NActions):
    ActualTorque = (A / NActions - 0.5) * 4
    return ActualTorque

def PendulumInverseActionConverter(A, NActions=NActions):
    ActualA = round((A + 2) * (NActions - 1) / 4)
    return(ActualA)

def OneEpisode(agent):
    env = gym.make(f'{EnvName}')
    S = env.reset()
    ListOfRewards = []
    Done = False
    step_count = 0
    
    while not Done:
        Q = agent.Main(S.reshape(-1, S.shape[0]))
        if np.random.rand() < Epsilon:
            AStep = env.action_space.sample()
            A = PendulumInverseActionConverter(AStep[0])
        else:
            A = np.argmax(Q)
            A = PendulumActionConverter(A)
            AStep = np.array([A])
            A = PendulumInverseActionConverter(A)
        
        SNext, R, Done, Info = env.step(AStep)
        agent.UpdateReplayMemory((S, A, R, SNext, Done))
        agent.Train(Done)
        ListOfRewards.append(R)
        S = SNext
        step_count += 1
    
    total_reward = np.sum(ListOfRewards)
    agent.record_episode_reward(total_reward)
    print(f'Finished! Return: {total_reward}')
    env.close()
    return total_reward
    
def plot_learning_curve(agent):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.plot(agent.return_history)
    plt.title('Learning Curve')
    plt.xlabel('Episode')
    plt.ylabel('Total Reward')
    plt.show()

def create_gif(agent):
    env = gym.make(f'{EnvName}')
    S = env.reset()
    ListOfRewards = []
    Done = False
    frames = []

    while not Done:
        Q = agent.Main(S.reshape(-1, S.shape[0]))
        if np.random.rand() < Epsilon:
            AStep = env.action_space.sample()
            A = PendulumInverseActionConverter(AStep[0])
        else:
            A = np.argmax(Q)
            A = PendulumActionConverter(A)
            AStep = np.array([A])
            A = PendulumInverseActionConverter(A)
        
        SNext, R, Done, Info = env.step(AStep)

        # Capture the frame after stepping
        frame = env.render(mode='rgb_array')
        frames.append(frame)

        agent.UpdateReplayMemory((S, A, R, SNext, Done))
        agent.Train(Done)
        ListOfRewards.append(R)
        S = SNext

    env.close()

    # Save frames as gif
    imageio.mimsave(f'./CA2-Output/RL-Training/{agent.name}_final.gif', frames, fps=30)

Baseline (Deep Q-Network)¶

DQN is a reinforcement learning algorithm that combines Q-learning with deep neural networks to handle high-dimensional state spaces. It approximates the Q-value function using a neural network, which predicts the expected reward for each action given a state.

Key Components of DQN¶

  • Q-Network

    • Input Layer: The current state of the environment.
    • Hidden Layers: Several layers to extract features from the state.
    • Output Layer: Q-values for each possible action.

  • Experience Replay

    • Replay Buffer: Stores agent's experiences (s, a, r, s').
    • Batch Training: Random mini-batches sampled from the buffer for training.

  • Target Network

    • Purpose: Provides stable Q-value targets.
    • Target Update: Updated periodically with the Q-Network's weights.

  • Bellman Equation and Loss Function

    • Q-learning Update Rule: $y = r + \gamma \max_{a'} Q(s', a'; \theta^-)$
    • Loss Function: $L(\theta) = \mathbb{E} \left[ (y - Q(s, a; \theta))^2 \right]$



In [ ]:
class DQN:
    def __init__(self,
                 InputShape = 3,
                 NActions = 2,
                 Gamma = 1,
                 ReplayMemorySize = 10000,
                 MinReplayMemory = 1000,
                 UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes = 1,
                 IntermediateSize = 64,
                 BatchSize = 32):
        self.name = 'Baseline'
        self.avg_return = 0
        
        # Hyperparameters. #
        self.InputShape = InputShape
        self.NActions = NActions
        self.Gamma = Gamma
        self.ReplayMemorySize = ReplayMemorySize
        self.MinReplayMemory = MinReplayMemory
        self.UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes = UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes
        self.IntermediateSize = IntermediateSize
        self.BatchSize = BatchSize
        self.return_history = []
        self.loss_history = []
        self.q_value_history = []
        self.gradient_history = []

        # Main model. #
        self.Main = self.CreateModel('Main')
        self.Optimiser = Adam()
        
        # Target model. #
        self.Target = self.CreateModel('Target')
        self.Target.set_weights(self.Main.get_weights())
        
        # Replay memory. #
        self.ReplayMemory = deque(maxlen = ReplayMemorySize)
        
        # Target network update counter. #
        self.TargetUpdateCounter = 0
    
    def record_episode_reward(self, episode_reward):
        self.return_history.append(episode_reward)
         
    def plot_magnitudes(self):
        # Create a DataFrame from our data
        df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Step': range(len(self.loss_history)),
            'Loss': self.loss_history,
            'Q-value': self.q_value_history,
            'Gradient': self.gradient_history
        })

        # Set up the plot style
        sns.set_style("whitegrid")
        sns.set_palette("deep")

        # Create the plot
        fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(20, 16))
        fig.suptitle('Learning Progress', fontsize=20)

        # Plot Loss, Q-value, and Gradient
        sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Step', y='Gradient', ax=axs[0, 0], color='blue')
        axs[0, 0].set_title('Gradient Over Step', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Loss separately
        sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Step', y='Loss', ax=axs[0, 1], color='red')
        axs[0, 1].set_title('Loss Over Step', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Q-value separately
        sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Step', y='Q-value', ax=axs[1, 0], color='green')
        axs[1, 0].set_title('Average Q-value Over Step', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Episode Reward
        return_df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Episode': range(len(self.return_history)),
            'Return': self.return_history
        })
        sns.lineplot(data=return_df, x='Episode', y='Return', ax=axs[1, 1], color='orange')
        axs[1, 1].set_title('Episode Return Over Time', fontsize=16)

        # Adjust layout and display
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
            
    def CreateModel(self, Type):
        inputs = Input(shape = (self.InputShape), name = 'Input')
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation = 'relu', name = '1stHiddenLayer')(inputs)
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation = 'relu', name = '2ndHiddenLayer')(x)
        outputs = Dense(self.NActions, activation = 'linear', name = 'Output')(x)
        
        NN = Model(inputs, outputs, name = f'{Type}')
        NN.summary()
        
        return NN
    
    def UpdateReplayMemory(self, Information): # Information = (S, A, R, SNext, Done)
        self.ReplayMemory.append(Information)

    def Train(self, EndOfEpisode):
        if len(self.ReplayMemory) < self.MinReplayMemory:
            return
        
        # Get batch of data for training. #
        TrainingData = random.sample(self.ReplayMemory, self.BatchSize)
        
        # Get states from training data, then get corresponding Q values. #
        ListOfS = np.array([element[0] for element in TrainingData])
        ListOfQ = np.array(self.Main(ListOfS))
        
        # Get future states from training data, then get corresponding Q values. #
        ListOfSNext = np.array([element[3] for element in TrainingData])
        ListOfQNext = self.Target(ListOfSNext)
        
        # Build actual training data for neural network. #
        X = []
        Y = []
        for index, (S, A, R, SNext, Done) in enumerate(TrainingData):
            if not Done:
                MaxQNext = np.max(ListOfQNext[index])
                QNext = R + self.Gamma * MaxQNext
            else:
                QNext = R
            Q = ListOfQ[index]
            Q[A] = QNext
        
            X.append(S)
            Y.append(Q)
        
        # Train model using tf.GradientTape(), defined below.
        Loss, Predictions, Grad = self.GTfit(X, Y)
        self.loss_history.append(float(Loss))
        self.q_value_history.append(float(tf.reduce_mean(Predictions)))
        self.gradient_history.append(float(tf.linalg.global_norm(Grad)))
                
        # Update target network every episode. #
        if EndOfEpisode:
            self.TargetUpdateCounter += 1
        
        # Update target if counter is full. #
        if self.TargetUpdateCounter >= self.UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes:
            self.Target.set_weights(self.Main.get_weights())
            self.TargetUpdateCounter = 0
    
    @tf.function
    def GTfit(self, X, Y):
        with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
            Predictions = self.Main(tf.convert_to_tensor(X), training=True)
            Loss = tf.math.reduce_mean(tf.math.square(tf.convert_to_tensor(Y) - Predictions))
        Grad = tape.gradient(Loss, self.Main.trainable_variables)
        self.Optimiser.apply_gradients(zip(Grad, self.Main.trainable_variables))
        return Loss, Predictions, Grad
In [ ]:
HyperParams = namedtuple('HyperParams', [
    'intermediate_size', 
    'learning_rate', 
    'gamma', 
    'batch_size', 
    'replay_memory_size',
    'min_replay_memory',
    'update_target_every'
])

# Define the hyperparameter search space
param_dist = {
    'intermediate_size': [32, 64, 128, 256, 512],
    'learning_rate': [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01],
    'gamma': [0.9, 0.95, 0.99],
    'batch_size': [32, 64, 128],
    'replay_memory_size': [10000, 50000, 100000],
    'min_replay_memory': [1000, 5000, 10000],
    'update_target_every': [5, 10, 20]
}

def sample_hyperparams():
    sampler = ParameterSampler(param_dist, n_iter=1, random_state=random.randint(1, 1000))
    params = next(iter(sampler))
    return HyperParams(**params)

def run_experiment(params, n_episodes=150, finalFlag=False):
    baseline = DQN(
        InputShape=InputShape, 
        NActions=NActions,
        IntermediateSize=params.intermediate_size,
        Gamma=params.gamma,
        ReplayMemorySize=params.replay_memory_size,
        MinReplayMemory=params.min_replay_memory,
        UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes=params.update_target_every,
        BatchSize=params.batch_size
    )
    
    baseline.Optimiser = Adam(learning_rate=params.learning_rate)
    
    returns = []
    for episode in range(n_episodes):
        if episode % ShowEvery == 0:
            print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
            
        result = OneEpisode(baseline)
        if isinstance(result, dict):
            # If OneEpisode returns a dict, we'll assume it contains the return
            returns.append(result.get('return', 0))
        elif len(baseline.return_history) > 0:
            returns.append(baseline.return_history[-1])

    if finalFlag:
        create_gif(baseline)
        baseline.plot_magnitudes()
        plt.show()
    
    avg_return = np.mean(returns) if returns else 0
    baseline.avg_return = avg_return
    return avg_return

n_configs = 5

best_params = None
best_avg_return = float('-inf')

for i in range(n_configs):
    params = sample_hyperparams()
    print(f"\nTrying configuration {i+1}/{n_configs}:")
    print(f"Params: {params}")
    
    avg_return = run_experiment(params)
    print(f"Average return: {avg_return:.2f}")
    
    if avg_return > best_avg_return:
        best_avg_return = avg_return
        best_params = params

print("\nBest hyperparameters found:")
print(f"Params: {best_params}")
print(f"Best average return: {best_avg_return:.2f}")

# Run a final experiment with the best parameters
print("\nRunning final experiment with best parameters...")
final_avg_return = run_experiment(best_params, finalFlag=True)
print(f"Final average return: {final_avg_return:.2f}")

Noisy DQN¶

Noisy DQN is an extension of the Deep Q-Network (DQN) that incorporates stochastic noise into the neural network's parameters to encourage exploration during training. This approach aims to address the challenge of balancing exploration and exploitation in reinforcement learning.

Key Components of Noisy DQN¶

  • Noisy Q-Network

    • Input Layer: The current state of the environment.
    • Hidden Layers: Several layers to extract features from the state.
    • Output Layer: Q-values for each possible action, with added noise to encourage exploration.

  • Noisy Layers

    • Noise Injection: Gaussian noise is added to the weights of the neural network to create a stochastic policy.
    • Learnable Parameters: The parameters of the noise distribution are learned during training, enabling adaptive exploration.

  • Experience Replay

    • Replay Buffer: Stores the agent's experiences (s, a, r, s').
    • Batch Training: Random mini-batches are sampled from the buffer for training, helping to break the correlation between consecutive experiences.

  • Target Network

    • Purpose: Provides stable Q-value targets to prevent oscillations or divergence during training.
    • Target Update: Updated periodically with the Q-Network's weights.

  • Bellman Equation and Loss Function

    • Q-learning Update Rule: $y = r + \gamma \max_{a'} Q(s', a'; \theta^-)$
    • Loss Function: $L(\theta) = \mathbb{E} \left[ (y - Q(s, a; \theta))^2 \right]$

  • Exploration vs. Exploitation

    • Adaptive Exploration: The noise parameters are optimized along with the Q-network weights, leading to a more effective balance between exploration and exploitation over time.
    • Reduced Dependence on ε-Greedy: Unlike traditional DQN that relies heavily on ε-greedy exploration, Noisy DQN uses parameter noise for more consistent exploration.

Advantages of Noisy DQN¶

  • Enhanced Exploration: By introducing noise directly into the network parameters, the agent is encouraged to explore more diverse actions.
  • Adaptive Mechanism: The learnable noise parameters allow the exploration strategy to adapt during training.
  • Improved Performance: Noisy DQN often leads to better performance in environments where effective exploration is crucial.

class NoisyDense(tf.keras.layers.Layer):
    def __init__(self, units, sigma=0.5, **kwargs):
        super(NoisyDense, self).__init__(**kwargs)
        self.units = units
        self.sigma = sigma

    def build(self, input_shape):
        self.w_mu = self.add_weight(name='w_mu', shape=(input_shape[-1], self.units),
                                    initializer='random_normal', trainable=True)
        self.w_sigma = self.add_weight(name='w_sigma', shape=(input_shape[-1], self.units),
                                       initializer=tf.constant_initializer(self.sigma), trainable=True)
        self.b_mu = self.add_weight(name='b_mu', shape=(self.units,),
                                    initializer='random_normal', trainable=True)
        self.b_sigma = self.add_weight(name='b_sigma', shape=(self.units,),
                                       initializer=tf.constant_initializer(self.sigma), trainable=True)

    def call(self, inputs, training=None):
        if training:
            w_noise = tf.random.normal(self.w_mu.shape)
            b_noise = tf.random.normal(self.b_mu.shape)
            return tf.matmul(inputs, self.w_mu + self.w_sigma * w_noise) + (self.b_mu + self.b_sigma * b_noise)
        return tf.matmul(inputs, self.w_mu) + self.b_mu

class NoisyDQN:
    def __init__(self,
                 InputShape=4,
                 NActions=2,
                 Gamma=1,
                 ReplayMemorySize=10000,
                 MinReplayMemory=1000,
                 UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes=1,
                 IntermediateSize=64,
                 BatchSize=32):
        self.name = 'NoisyDQN'
        self.avg_return = 0
        
        # Hyperparameters. #
        self.InputShape = InputShape
        self.NActions = NActions
        self.Gamma = Gamma
        self.ReplayMemorySize = ReplayMemorySize
        self.MinReplayMemory = MinReplayMemory
        self.UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes = UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes
        self.IntermediateSize = IntermediateSize
        self.BatchSize = BatchSize
        self.return_history = []
        self.loss_history = []
        self.q_value_history = []
        self.gradient_history = []

        # Main model. #
        self.Main = self.CreateModel('Main')
        self.Optimiser = Adam()
        
        # Target model. #
        self.Target = self.CreateModel('Target')
        self.Target.set_weights(self.Main.get_weights())
        
        # Replay memory. #
        self.ReplayMemory = deque(maxlen=ReplayMemorySize)
        
        # Target network update counter. #
        self.TargetUpdateCounter = 0
    
    def record_episode_reward(self, episode_reward):
        self.return_history.append(episode_reward)
         
    def plot_magnitudes(self):
        # Create a DataFrame from our data
        df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Step': range(len(self.loss_history)),
            'Loss': self.loss_history,
            'Q-value': self.q_value_history,
            'Gradient': self.gradient_history
        })

        # Set up the plot style
        sns.set_style("whitegrid")
        sns.set_palette("deep")

        # Create the plot
        fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(20, 16))
        fig.suptitle('Learning Progress', fontsize=20)

        # Plot Gradient
        sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Step', y='Gradient', ax=axs[0, 0], color='blue')
        axs[0, 0].set_title('Gradient Over Step', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Loss
        sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Step', y='Loss', ax=axs[0, 1], color='red')
        axs[0, 1].set_title('Loss Over Step', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Q-value
        sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Step', y='Q-value', ax=axs[1, 0], color='green')
        axs[1, 0].set_title('Average Q-value Over Step', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Episode Return
        return_df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Episode': range(len(self.return_history)),
            'Return': self.return_history
        })
        sns.lineplot(data=return_df, x='Episode', y='Return', ax=axs[1, 1], color='orange')
        axs[1, 1].set_title('Episode Return Over Time', fontsize=16)

        # Adjust layout and display
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
        
    def CreateModel(self, Type):
        inputs = Input(shape=(self.InputShape,), name='Input')
        x = NoisyDense(self.IntermediateSize, name='1stHiddenLayer')(inputs)
        x = Activation('relu')(x)
        x = NoisyDense(self.IntermediateSize, name='2ndHiddenLayer')(x)
        x = Activation('relu')(x)
        outputs = Dense(self.NActions, activation='linear', name='Output')(x)
        
        NN = Model(inputs, outputs, name=f'{Type}')
        NN.summary()
        
        return NN
    
    def UpdateReplayMemory(self, Information): # Information = (S, A, R, SNext, Done)
        self.ReplayMemory.append(Information)

    def Train(self, EndOfEpisode):
        if len(self.ReplayMemory) < self.MinReplayMemory:
            return
        
        # Get batch of data for training. #
        TrainingData = random.sample(self.ReplayMemory, self.BatchSize)
        
        # Get states from training data, then get corresponding Q values. #
        ListOfS = np.array([element[0] for element in TrainingData])
        ListOfQ = np.array(self.Main(ListOfS))
        
        # Get future states from training data, then get corresponding Q values. #
        ListOfSNext = np.array([element[3] for element in TrainingData])
        ListOfQNext = self.Target(ListOfSNext)
        
        # Build actual training data for neural network. #
        X = []
        Y = []
        for index, (S, A, R, SNext, Done) in enumerate(TrainingData):
            if not Done:
                MaxQNext = np.max(ListOfQNext[index])
                QNext = R + self.Gamma * MaxQNext
            else:
                QNext = R
            Q = ListOfQ[index]
            Q[A] = QNext
        
            X.append(S)
            Y.append(Q)
        
        # Train model using tf.GradientTape(), defined below.
        Loss, Predictions, Grad = self.GTfit(X, Y)
        self.loss_history.append(float(Loss))
        self.q_value_history.append(float(tf.reduce_mean(Predictions)))
        self.gradient_history.append(float(tf.linalg.global_norm(Grad)))
                
        # Update target network every episode. #
        if EndOfEpisode:
            self.TargetUpdateCounter += 1
        
        # Update target if counter is full. #
        if self.TargetUpdateCounter >= self.UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes:
            self.Target.set_weights(self.Main.get_weights())
            self.TargetUpdateCounter = 0
    
    @tf.function
    def GTfit(self, X, Y):
        with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
            Predictions = self.Main(tf.convert_to_tensor(X), training=True)
            Loss = tf.math.reduce_mean(tf.math.square(tf.convert_to_tensor(Y) - Predictions))
        Grad = tape.gradient(Loss, self.Main.trainable_variables)
        self.Optimiser.apply_gradients(zip(Grad, self.Main.trainable_variables))
        return Loss, Predictions, Grad
In [ ]:
HyperParams = namedtuple('HyperParams', [
    'intermediate_size', 
    'learning_rate', 
    'gamma', 
    'batch_size', 
    'replay_memory_size',
    'min_replay_memory',
    'update_target_every',
    'sigma'
])

# Define the hyperparameter search space
param_dist = {
    'intermediate_size': [32, 64, 128, 256, 512],
    'learning_rate': [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01],
    'gamma': [0.9, 0.95, 0.99],
    'batch_size': [32, 64, 128],
    'replay_memory_size': [10000, 20000, 30000],
    'min_replay_memory': [1000, 2000, 4000],
    'update_target_every': [5, 10, 20],
    'sigma': [0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 1.0]  # Added sigma values for NoisyDQN
}

def sample_hyperparams():
    sampler = ParameterSampler(param_dist, n_iter=1, random_state=random.randint(1, 1000))
    params = next(iter(sampler))
    return HyperParams(**params)

def run_experiment(params, n_episodes=150, finalFlag=False):
    # Assuming InputShape and NActions are defined elsewhere
    noisyDQN = NoisyDQN(
        InputShape=InputShape, 
        NActions=NActions
    )
    
    noisyDQN.Optimiser = Adam(learning_rate=params.learning_rate)
    
    # Update sigma for NoisyDense layers
    for layer in noisyDQN.Main.layers:
        if isinstance(layer, NoisyDense):
            layer.sigma = params.sigma
    
    returns = []
    for episode in range(n_episodes):
        if episode % ShowEvery == 0:
            print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
            
        result = OneEpisode(noisyDQN)
        if isinstance(result, dict):
            # If OneEpisode returns a dict, we'll assume it contains the return
            returns.append(result.get('return', 0))
        elif len(noisyDQN.return_history) > 0:
            returns.append(noisyDQN.return_history[-1])

    if finalFlag:
        create_gif(noisyDQN)
        noisyDQN.plot_magnitudes()
        plt.show()
    
    avg_return = np.mean(returns) if returns else 0
    noisyDQN.avg_return = avg_return
    return avg_return

n_configs = 3

best_params = None
best_avg_return = float('-inf')

for i in range(n_configs):
    params = sample_hyperparams()
    print(f"\nTrying configuration {i+1}/{n_configs}:")
    print(f"Params: {params}")
    
    avg_return = run_experiment(params)
    print(f"Average return: {avg_return:.2f}")
    
    if avg_return > best_avg_return:
        best_avg_return = avg_return
        best_params = params

print("\nBest hyperparameters found:")
print(f"Params: {best_params}")
print(f"Best average return: {best_avg_return:.2f}")

# Run a final experiment with the best parameters
print("\nRunning final experiment with best parameters...")
final_avg_return = run_experiment(best_params, n_episodes=150, finalFlag=True)
print(f"Final average return: {final_avg_return:.2f}")

Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient (DDPG)¶

Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient (DDPG) is a model-free, off-policy reinforcement learning algorithm designed for environments with continuous action spaces. DDPG combines aspects of both Q-learning and policy gradient methods, using an actor-critic architecture. The main components include the Actor Network, Critic Network, Experience Replay, and Target Networks.

Key Components of DDPG¶

  • Actor Network

    • Input Layer: Receives the current state.
    • Hidden Layers: Extract features from the state.
    • Output Layer: Outputs a specific action for the given state.

  • Critic Network

    • Input Layer: Receives the state and action.
    • Hidden Layers: Processes state-action pairs.
    • Output Layer: Outputs the Q-value representing the value of the action-state pair.

  • Experience Replay

    • Replay Buffer: Stores experiences (s, a, r, s').
    • Batch Training: Random mini-batches are used to train the networks.

  • Target Networks

    • Target Actor Network: $ \mu'(s|\theta^{\mu'}) $
    • Target Critic Network: $ Q'(s, a|\theta^{Q'}) $
    • Soft Updates: $\theta' \leftarrow \tau \theta + (1 - \tau)\theta'$ where $ \tau $ is a small parameter.

  • Exploration Strategy

    • Noise Process: Typically uses the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process to add noise to actions, encouraging exploration.

class DDPG:
    def __init__(self,
                 InputShape=3,
                 NActions=1,
                 Gamma=0.99,
                 ReplayMemorySize=10000,
                 MinReplayMemory=1000,
                 UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes=1,
                 ActorLearningRate=0.001,
                 CriticLearningRate=0.002,
                 IntermediateSize=64,
                 BatchSize=64,
                 Tau=0.005):
        self.name = 'DDPG'
        self.avg_return = 0
        
        # Hyperparameters
        self.InputShape = InputShape
        self.NActions = NActions
        self.Gamma = Gamma
        self.ReplayMemorySize = ReplayMemorySize
        self.MinReplayMemory = MinReplayMemory
        self.UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes = UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes
        self.ActorLearningRate = ActorLearningRate
        self.CriticLearningRate = CriticLearningRate
        self.IntermediateSize = IntermediateSize
        self.BatchSize = BatchSize
        self.Tau = Tau

        # History
        self.return_history = []
        self.loss_history = []
        self.q_value_history = []
        self.gradient_history = []
        self.sd_history = []

        # Actor and Critic models
        self.Actor = self.create_actor('Actor')
        self.Critic = self.create_critic('Critic')
        
        # Target models
        self.TargetActor = self.create_actor('TargetActor')
        self.TargetActor.set_weights(self.Actor.get_weights())
        self.TargetCritic = self.create_critic('TargetCritic')
        self.TargetCritic.set_weights(self.Critic.get_weights())
        
        # Optimizers
        self.ActorOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=self.ActorLearningRate)
        self.CriticOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=self.CriticLearningRate)
        
        # Replay memory
        self.ReplayMemory = deque(maxlen=self.ReplayMemorySize)
        
        # Target network update counter
        self.TargetUpdateCounter = 0
    
    def record_episode_reward(self, episode_reward):
        self.return_history.append(episode_reward)
    
    def create_actor(self, name):
        inputs = Input(shape=(self.InputShape,))
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation='relu')(inputs)
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation='relu')(x)
        outputs = Dense(self.NActions, activation='tanh')(x)
        model = Model(inputs, outputs, name=name)
        return model

    def create_critic(self, name):
        state_input = Input(shape=(self.InputShape,))
        action_input = Input(shape=(self.NActions,))
        concat = tf.concat([state_input, action_input], axis=-1)
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation='relu')(concat)
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation='relu')(x)
        outputs = Dense(1)(x)
        model = Model([state_input, action_input], outputs, name=name)
        return model

    def update_replay_memory(self, information):  # Information = (S, A, R, SNext, Done)
        self.ReplayMemory.append(information)

    def train(self, end_of_episode):
        if len(self.ReplayMemory) < self.MinReplayMemory:
            return
        
        # Get batch of data for training
        training_data = random.sample(self.ReplayMemory, self.BatchSize)
        
        # Get states, actions, rewards, next states, and done flags from training data
        states = np.array([data[0] for data in training_data])
        actions = np.array([data[1] for data in training_data])
        rewards = np.array([data[2] for data in training_data])
        next_states = np.array([data[3] for data in training_data])
        dones = np.array([data[4] for data in training_data])
        
        # Update critic
        next_actions = self.TargetActor(next_states)
        q_next = self.TargetCritic([next_states, next_actions])
        q_targets = rewards + self.Gamma * q_next * (1 - dones)
        with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
            q_values = self.Critic([states, actions])
            critic_loss = tf.reduce_mean(tf.square(q_targets - q_values))
        critic_grads = tape.gradient(critic_loss, self.Critic.trainable_variables)
        self.CriticOptimizer.apply_gradients(zip(critic_grads, self.Critic.trainable_variables))
        
        # Update actor
        with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
            actions_pred = self.Actor(states)
            actor_loss = -tf.reduce_mean(self.Critic([states, actions_pred]))
        actor_grads = tape.gradient(actor_loss, self.Actor.trainable_variables)
        self.ActorOptimizer.apply_gradients(zip(actor_grads, self.Actor.trainable_variables))
        
        # Soft update target networks
        self.update_target_network(self.TargetActor, self.Actor)
        self.update_target_network(self.TargetCritic, self.Critic)
        
        # Record history
        self.loss_history.append(float(critic_loss))
        self.q_value_history.append(float(tf.reduce_mean(q_values)))
        self.gradient_history.append(float(tf.linalg.global_norm(critic_grads)))
                
        if end_of_episode:
            self.TargetUpdateCounter += 1
    
    def update_target_network(self, target, source):
        target_weights = target.get_weights()
        source_weights = source.get_weights()
        new_weights = [(1 - self.Tau) * target_weight + self.Tau * source_weight for target_weight, source_weight in zip(target_weights, source_weights)]
        target.set_weights(new_weights)
        
    def plot_magnitudes(self):
        # Create a DataFrame from our data
        df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Step': range(len(self.loss_history)),
            'Loss': self.loss_history,
            'Q-value': self.q_value_history,
            'Gradient': self.gradient_history
        })

        # Set up the plot style
        sns.set_style("whitegrid")
        sns.set_palette("deep")

        # Create the plot
        fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(20, 16))
        fig.suptitle('Learning Progress', fontsize=20)

        # Plot Loss, Q-value, and Gradient
        sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Step', y='Gradient', ax=axs[0, 0], color='blue')
        axs[0, 0].set_title('Gradient Over Step', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Loss separately
        sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Step', y='Loss', ax=axs[0, 1], color='red')
        axs[0, 1].set_title('Loss Over Step', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Q-value separately
        sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Step', y='Q-value', ax=axs[1, 0], color='green')
        axs[1, 0].set_title('Average Q-value Over Step', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Episode Reward
        return_df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Episode': range(len(self.return_history)),
            'Return': self.return_history
        })
        sns.lineplot(data=return_df, x='Episode', y='Return', ax=axs[1, 1], color='orange')
        axs[1, 1].set_title('Episode Return Over Time', fontsize=16)

        # Adjust layout and display
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

def pendulum_action_converter(a, n_actions):
    return (a / n_actions - 0.5) * 4

def pendulum_inverse_action_converter(a, n_actions):
    return round((a + 2) * (n_actions - 1) / 4)

def one_episode(agent, env, epsilon=0.1):
    state = env.reset()
    state = state.reshape(1, -1)  # Reshape state to (1, state_dim)
    list_of_rewards = []
    done = False
    truncated = False
    while not (done or truncated):
        if np.random.rand() < epsilon:
            action = env.action_space.sample()
        else:
            action = agent.Actor(state).numpy()[0]

        # Adapt to the environment's step function
        try:
            next_state, reward, done, truncated, _ = env.step(action)
        except ValueError:
            next_state, reward, done, _ = env.step(action)
            truncated = False  # Handle missing truncated flag
        
        next_state = next_state.reshape(1, -1)  # Reshape next_state to (1, state_dim)
        
        agent.update_replay_memory((state[0], action, reward, next_state[0], done))
        agent.train(done or truncated)
        list_of_rewards.append(reward)
        
        Total_Reward = np.sum(list_of_rewards)
        SD_Reward = np.std(list_of_rewards)

        if done or truncated:
            agent.sd_history.append(SD_Reward)
            agent.return_history.append(Total_Reward)
            print(f'Finished! Return: {Total_Reward}')
            return Total_Reward
        
        state = next_state


def create_ddpg_gif(agent, epsilon=0.1):
    env = gym.make(f'{EnvName}')
    state = env.reset()
    state = state.reshape(1, -1)  # Reshape state to (1, state_dim)
    done = False
    truncated = False
    frames = []
    
    while not (done or truncated):
        if np.random.rand() < epsilon:
            action = env.action_space.sample()
        else:
            action = agent.Actor(state).numpy()[0]

        # Adapt to the environment's step function
        try:
            next_state, reward, done, truncated, _ = env.step(action)
        except ValueError:
            next_state, reward, done, _ = env.step(action)
            truncated = False  # Handle missing truncated flag
        
        frame = env.render(mode='rgb_array')
        frames.append(frame)
        next_state = next_state.reshape(1, -1)  # Reshape next_state to (1, state_dim)
        
        agent.update_replay_memory((state[0], action, reward, next_state[0], done))
        agent.train(done or truncated)        
        state = next_state

    imageio.mimsave(f'./CA2-Output/RL-Training/{agent.name}_.gif', frames, fps=30)
    env.close()
    # Save frames as gif

HyperParams = namedtuple('HyperParams', [
    'input_shape', 'n_actions', 'gamma', 'replay_memory_size', 'min_replay_memory',
    'update_target_every_this_episodes', 'actor_learning_rate', 'critic_learning_rate',
    'intermediate_size', 'batch_size', 'tau'
])

def random_hyperparams():
    return HyperParams(
        input_shape=None, 
        n_actions=None, 
        gamma=random.choice([0.95, 0.99, 0.999]),
        replay_memory_size=random.choice([10000, 20000, 25000]),
        min_replay_memory=random.choice([1000, 2000, 2500]),
        update_target_every_this_episodes=random.choice([1, 2, 5]),
        actor_learning_rate=random.choice([0.0001, 0.001, 0.01]),
        critic_learning_rate=random.choice([0.0002, 0.002, 0.02]),
        intermediate_size=random.choice([32, 64, 128, 256]),
        batch_size=random.choice([32, 64, 128]),
        tau=random.choice([0.001, 0.005, 0.01])
    )

def run_experiment(params, n_episodes=150, finalFlag=False):
    env = gym.make("Pendulum-v0")
    params = params._replace(input_shape=env.observation_space.shape[0], n_actions=env.action_space.shape[0])
    
    ddpg = DDPG(InputShape=params.input_shape, 
                NActions=params.n_actions,
                Gamma=params.gamma,
                ReplayMemorySize=params.replay_memory_size,
                MinReplayMemory=params.min_replay_memory,
                UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes=params.update_target_every_this_episodes,
                ActorLearningRate=params.actor_learning_rate,
                CriticLearningRate=params.critic_learning_rate,
                IntermediateSize=params.intermediate_size,
                BatchSize=params.batch_size,
                Tau=params.tau)
    
    returns = []
    ShowEvery = 3
    for episode in range(n_episodes):
        if episode % ShowEvery == 0:
            print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
        one_episode(ddpg, env)
        if len(ddpg.return_history) > 0:
            returns.append(ddpg.return_history[-1])
    if finalFlag:
        create_ddpg_gif(ddpg)
        ddpg.plot_magnitudes()
        plt.show()
    avg_return = sum(returns) / len(returns) if returns else 0
    ddpg.avg_return = avg_return
    return avg_return

n_configs = 3  # Number of random iterations

best_params = None
best_avg_return = float('-inf')

for i in range(n_configs):
    params = random_hyperparams()
    print(f"\nTrying configuration {i+1}/{n_configs}:")
    print(f"Gamma: {params.gamma}, "
          f"ReplayMemorySize: {params.replay_memory_size}, "
          f"MinReplayMemory: {params.min_replay_memory}, "
          f"UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes: {params.update_target_every_this_episodes}, "
          f"ActorLearningRate: {params.actor_learning_rate}, "
          f"CriticLearningRate: {params.critic_learning_rate}, "
          f"IntermediateSize: {params.intermediate_size}, "
          f"BatchSize: {params.batch_size}, "
          f"Tau: {params.tau}")
    
    avg_return = run_experiment(params)
    print(f"Average return: {avg_return:.2f}")
    
    if avg_return > best_avg_return:
        best_avg_return = avg_return
        best_params = params

print("\nBest hyperparameters found:")
for field in best_params._fields:
    if field not in ['input_shape', 'n_actions']:
        print(f"{field}: {getattr(best_params, field)}")
print(f"Best average return: {best_avg_return:.2f}")

# Run a final experiment with the best parameters
print("\nRunning final experiment with best parameters...")
final_avg_return = run_experiment(best_params, finalFlag=True)
print(f"Final average return: {final_avg_return:.2f}")

compared_agents = pd.DataFrame(compared_agents)

def highlight_max(dataframe):
    max_return_index = dataframe["Average Return"].idxmax()
    return pd.DataFrame([['background-color: yellow' if i == max_return_index else '' for i in range(len(dataframe))]], index=[''])

styled_df = compared_agents.style.apply(highlight_max, axis=0)

styled_df = compared_agents.style.apply(lambda x: ['background-color: Green' if x.name == compared_agents["Average Return"].idxmax() else '' for _ in x], axis=1)

Model Improvement¶

Hyper Parameter¶

  • Learning Rates (ActorLearningRate & CriticLearningRate) - These are crucial because they determine how quickly the actor and critic networks learn. The actor updates the policy based on the gradient of expected return, and the critic updates the value function estimates. Inappropriate rates can lead to diverging or very slow learning.
  • Gamma (Discount Factor) - This parameter influences how much the agent values immediate rewards versus future rewards. A higher gamma makes the agent prioritize future rewards more heavily, potentially improving long-term strategies.
  • Intermediate Size - Typically refers to the dimensions of hidden layers in the neural networks. This can affect the model's capacity to learn complex policies but is often less sensitive than other parameters.
  • Batch Size - Influences the stability of learning by determining how many experiences are used to update the network at once. Larger batch sizes can provide more stable, but possibly slower, updates.



Tune Learning Rate¶

In [ ]:
# Learning rate hyperparameter search
learning_rates = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1]
best_lr = None
best_avg_return = -np.inf
n_episodes = 100
DF_learningRate = {
    'Learning Rate': [],
    'Average Return': []
}

for lr in learning_rates:
    print(f"Testing learning rate: {lr}")
    env = gym.make("Pendulum-v0")
    agent = DDPG()
    agent.ActorOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=lr)
    agent.CriticOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=lr)
    returns = []
    for episode in range(n_episodes):
        if episode % ShowEvery == 0:
            print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
        result = one_episode(agent, env)
        returns.append(result)
    DF_learningRate['Average Return'].append(np.mean(returns))
    DF_learningRate['Learning Rate'].append(lr)
    avg_return = np.mean(returns) if returns else 0
    print(f"Average return: {avg_return}")
    best_lr = max(DF_learningRate["Learning Rate"])
    best_avg_return = max(DF_learningRate["Average Return"])
    
print(f"Best learning rate: {best_lr} with average return: {best_avg_return}")

Tune Gamma¶

In [ ]:
# Gamma hyperparameter search
gammas = [0.9, 0.95, 0.99]
best_gamma = None
best_avg_return = -np.inf
n_episodes = 100
ShowEvery = 1  # Adjust this as needed

DF_Gamma = {
    'Gamma': [],
    'Average Return': []
}

for gamma in gammas:
    print(f"Testing Gamma: {gamma}")
    agent = DDPG(Gamma=gamma)
    agent.ActorOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=best_lr)
    agent.CriticOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=best_lr)
    returns = []
    for episode in range(n_episodes):
        if episode % ShowEvery == 0:
            print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
        result = one_episode(agent, env)
        returns.append(result)
    avg_return = np.mean(returns) if returns else 0
    DF_Gamma['Average Return'].append(avg_return)
    DF_Gamma['Gamma'].append(gamma)
    print(f"Average return: {avg_return}")
    if avg_return > best_avg_return:
        best_avg_return = avg_return
        best_gamma = gamma

print(f"Best Gamma: {best_gamma} with average return: {best_avg_return}")

Tune Batch Size¶

In [ ]:
# Batch Size hyperparameter search
batch_sizes = [16, 32, 64]
best_batch_size = None
best_avg_return = -np.inf
n_episodes = 100
ShowEvery = 1  # Adjust this as needed

DF_BatchSize = {
    'Batch Size': [],
    'Average Return': []
}

for batch_size in batch_sizes:
    print(f"Testing Batch Size: {batch_size}")
    agent = DDPG(BatchSize=batch_size)
    agent.ActorOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=best_lr)
    agent.CriticOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=best_lr)
    agent.Gamma = best_gamma
    returns = []
    for episode in range(n_episodes):
        if episode % ShowEvery == 0:
            print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
        result = one_episode(agent, env)
        returns.append(result)
    avg_return = np.mean(returns) if returns else 0
    DF_BatchSize['Average Return'].append(avg_return)
    DF_BatchSize['Batch Size'].append(batch_size)
    print(f"Average return: {avg_return}")
    if avg_return > best_avg_return:
        best_avg_return = avg_return
        best_batch_size = batch_size

print(f"Best Batch Size: {best_batch_size} with average return: {best_avg_return}")

Tune Intermediate Size¶

In [ ]:
# Intermediate Size hyperparameter search
intermediate_sizes = [32, 64, 128]
best_intermediate_size = None
best_avg_return = -np.inf
n_episodes = 100
ShowEvery = 1  # Adjust this as needed

DF_IntermediateSize = {
    'Intermediate Size': [],
    'Average Return': []
}

for intermediate_size in intermediate_sizes:
    print(f"Testing Intermediate Size: {intermediate_size}")
    agent = DDPG(IntermediateSize=intermediate_size)
    agent.ActorOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=best_lr)
    agent.CriticOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=best_lr)
    agent.Gamma = best_gamma
    agent.BatchSize = best_batch_size
    returns = []
    for episode in range(n_episodes):
        if episode % ShowEvery == 0:
            print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
        result = one_episode(agent, env)
        returns.append(result)
    avg_return = np.mean(returns) if returns else 0
    DF_IntermediateSize['Average Return'].append(avg_return)
    DF_IntermediateSize['Intermediate Size'].append(intermediate_size)
    print(f"Average return: {avg_return}")
    if avg_return > best_avg_return:
        best_avg_return = avg_return
        best_intermediate_size = intermediate_size

print(f"Best Intermediate Size: {best_intermediate_size} with average return: {best_avg_return}")

Ornstein-Uhlenbeck Process (OU Noise)¶

The OU process is a type of noise that is temporally correlated. It was originally developed to model the velocity of a Brownian particle with friction. This makes it particularly useful for physical control tasks where smooth actions are preferred. it adds noise to the action outputs. This helps to improve exploration of the action space by the agent. Let's break down how it works:

$$ dx_t = \theta (\mu - x_t) dt + \sigma dW_t $$

Where:

  • $ x_t $ is the current value of the noise.
  • $ \theta $ is a rate that pulls $ x_t $ towards the mean $ \mu $.
  • $ \mu $ is the mean, towards which the process reverts.
  • $ \sigma $ is the scale of the noise.
  • $ dW_t $ represents the increment of a Wiener process (i.e., Gaussian noise).

Application in DDPG¶

In the context of DDPG, the OU Noise is applied to the action outputs of the actor network to encourage exploration of the action space. Here’s why it’s particularly useful:

  • Temporal Correlation: Because the noise is temporally correlated, the exploration is more coherent across time steps, as opposed to independent random exploration (e.g., Gaussian noise) which could lead to jerky and erratic exploration patterns.
  • Reversion to Mean: The reversion to the mean allows the noise not to wander off too far from zero, which helps in maintaining reasonable exploration around the action values proposed by the policy.

Adding such noise helps the agent to explore various strategies and prevents it from getting stuck in suboptimal policy loops, especially during the early stages of training when the policy is still immature. This is crucial for environments where exploring a wide variety of actions is necessary for learning effective strategies.

In [ ]:
class OUNoise:
    def __init__(self, action_dimension, mu=0, theta=0.15, sigma=0.2):
        self.action_dimension = action_dimension
        self.mu = mu
        self.theta = theta
        self.sigma = sigma
        self.state = np.ones(action_dimension) * mu
        self.reset()

    def reset(self):
        self.state = np.ones(self.action_dimension) * self.mu

    def noise(self):
        x = self.state
        dx = self.theta * (self.mu - x) + self.sigma * np.random.randn(self.action_dimension)
        self.state = x + dx
        return self.state
In [ ]:
def one_episode(agent, env, epsilon=0.1):
    state = env.reset()
    state = state.reshape(1, -1)
    list_of_rewards = []
    done = False
    truncated = False
    noise_process = OUNoise(agent.NActions)

    while not (done or truncated):
        pure_action = agent.Actor(state).numpy()[0]
        noise = noise_process.noise()
        action = np.clip(pure_action + noise, env.action_space.low, env.action_space.high)  # Clip actions to valid range

        try:
            next_state, reward, done, truncated, _ = env.step(action)
        except ValueError:
            next_state, reward, done, _ = env.step(action)
            truncated = False  # Handle missing truncated flag
        
        next_state = next_state.reshape(1, -1)  # Reshape next_state to (1, state_dim)
        
        agent.update_replay_memory((state[0], action, reward, next_state[0], done))
        agent.train(done or truncated)
        list_of_rewards.append(reward)
        
        Total_Reward = np.sum(list_of_rewards)
        SD_Reward = np.std(list_of_rewards)

        if done or truncated:
            agent.sd_history.append(SD_Reward)
            agent.return_history.append(Total_Reward)
            print(f'Finished! Return: {Total_Reward}')
            return Total_Reward
        
        state = next_state

class ImprovedDDPG:
    def __init__(self, InputShape=3, 
                 NActions=1,
                 Gamma=0.99, 
                 ReplayMemorySize=10000, 
                 MinReplayMemory=2000,
                 UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes=1, 
                 ActorLearningRate=0.0001,  # Adjusted Learning Rates
                 CriticLearningRate=0.0002, 
                 IntermediateSize=128,  # Increased Intermediate Size
                 BatchSize=64,  # Adjusted Batch Size
                 Tau=0.01,  # Adjusted Tau
                 NoiseDecay=0.995):
        self.name = 'ImprovedDDPG'
        self.avg_return = 0

        # Initialize parameters
        self.InputShape = InputShape
        self.NActions = NActions
        self.Gamma = Gamma
        self.ReplayMemorySize = ReplayMemorySize
        self.MinReplayMemory = MinReplayMemory
        self.UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes = UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes
        self.ActorLearningRate = ActorLearningRate
        self.CriticLearningRate = CriticLearningRate
        self.IntermediateSize = IntermediateSize
        self.BatchSize = BatchSize
        self.Tau = Tau
        self.NoiseDecay = NoiseDecay
        self.noise_std = 1.0  # Initial noise standard deviation

        # Initialize history tracking
        self.return_history = []
        self.loss_history = []
        self.q_value_history = []
        self.gradient_history = []
        self.sd_history = []

        # Build models and optimizers
        self.Actor, self.Critic = self.create_actor_critic()
        self.TargetActor, self.TargetCritic = self.create_actor_critic()
        self.TargetActor.set_weights(self.Actor.get_weights())
        self.TargetCritic.set_weights(self.Critic.get_weights())
        self.ActorOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=self.ActorLearningRate)
        self.CriticOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=self.CriticLearningRate)

        # Replay memory
        self.ReplayMemory = deque(maxlen=self.ReplayMemorySize)

        # Target network update counter
        self.TargetUpdateCounter = 0

    def create_actor_critic(self):
        # Actor
        actor_inputs = Input(shape=(self.InputShape,))
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.01))(actor_inputs)
        x = BatchNormalization()(x)
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.01))(x)
        x = BatchNormalization()(x)
        actor_outputs = Dense(self.NActions, activation='tanh')(x)
        actor = Model(actor_inputs, actor_outputs, name='Actor')

        # Critic
        state_input = Input(shape=(self.InputShape,))
        action_input = Input(shape=(self.NActions,))
        concat = tf.concat([state_input, action_input], axis=-1)
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.01))(concat)
        x = BatchNormalization()(x)
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.01))(x)
        x = BatchNormalization()(x)
        critic_outputs = Dense(1)(x)
        critic = Model([state_input, action_input], critic_outputs, name='Critic')

        return actor, critic
    
    def update_replay_memory(self, information):  # Information = (S, A, R, SNext, Done)
        self.ReplayMemory.append(information)

    def train(self, end_of_episode):
        if len(self.ReplayMemory) < self.MinReplayMemory:
            return

        # Get batch of data for training
        training_data = random.sample(self.ReplayMemory, self.BatchSize)
        
        # Get states, actions, rewards, next states, and done flags from training data
        states = np.array([data[0] for data in training_data])
        actions = np.array([data[1] for data in training_data])
        rewards = np.array([data[2] for data in training_data])
        next_states = np.array([data[3] for data in training_data])
        dones = np.array([data[4] for data in training_data])
        
        # Normalize rewards
        rewards = (rewards - np.mean(rewards)) / (np.std(rewards) + 1e-6)

        # Update critic with Huber loss
        next_actions = self.TargetActor(next_states)
        q_next = self.TargetCritic([next_states, next_actions])
        q_targets = rewards + self.Gamma * q_next * (1 - dones)
        with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
            q_values = self.Critic([states, actions])
            critic_loss = tf.reduce_mean(tf.keras.losses.huber(q_targets, q_values))
        critic_grads = tape.gradient(critic_loss, self.Critic.trainable_variables)
        critic_grads = [tf.clip_by_value(grad, -1.0, 1.0) for grad in critic_grads]  # Gradient clipping
        self.CriticOptimizer.apply_gradients(zip(critic_grads, self.Critic.trainable_variables))
        
        # Update actor
        with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
            actions_pred = self.Actor(states)
            actor_loss = -tf.reduce_mean(self.Critic([states, actions_pred]))
        actor_grads = tape.gradient(actor_loss, self.Actor.trainable_variables)
        actor_grads = [tf.clip_by_value(grad, -1.0, 1.0) for grad in actor_grads]  # Gradient clipping
        self.ActorOptimizer.apply_gradients(zip(actor_grads, self.Actor.trainable_variables))
        
        # Soft update target networks
        self.update_target_network(self.TargetActor, self.Actor)
        self.update_target_network(self.TargetCritic, self.Critic)
        
        # Record history
        self.loss_history.append(float(critic_loss))
        self.q_value_history.append(float(tf.reduce_mean(q_values)))
        self.gradient_history.append(float(tf.linalg.global_norm(critic_grads)))
                
        if end_of_episode:
            self.TargetUpdateCounter += 1
            self.noise_std *= self.NoiseDecay  # Decay noise
    
    def update_target_network(self, target, source):
        target_weights = target.get_weights()
        source_weights = source.get_weights()
        new_weights = [(1 - self.Tau) * target_weight + self.Tau * source_weight for target_weight, source_weight in zip(target_weights, source_weights)]
        target.set_weights(new_weights)
        
    def calculate_reward_statistics(self):
        if self.all_rewards:
            mean_reward = np.mean(self.all_rewards)
            std_reward = np.std(self.all_rewards)
            print(f"Mean Reward: {mean_reward}, Standard Deviation of Reward: {std_reward}")
            return mean_reward, std_reward
        else:
            return 0, 0
        
    def plot_magnitudes(self):
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 12))  # Set the figure size
        gs = GridSpec(3, 2)  # Define a grid with 3 rows and 2 columns

        # Create the top subplot for Episode Return
        ax_top = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, :])  # Span all columns of the first row
        return_df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Episode': range(len(self.return_history)),
            'Return': self.return_history
        })
        sns.lineplot(data=return_df, x='Episode', y='Return', ax=ax_top)
        ax_top.set_title('Episode Return Over Time', fontsize=16)

        # Create subplots for the rest
        # Plot Gradient
        ax1 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 0])  # Second row, first column
        sns.lineplot(data=pd.DataFrame({
            'Step': range(len(self.gradient_history)),
            'Gradient': self.gradient_history
        }), x='Step', y='Gradient', ax=ax1, color='blue')
        ax1.set_title('Gradient Over Steps', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Loss
        ax2 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 1])  # Second row, second column
        sns.lineplot(data=pd.DataFrame({
            'Step': range(len(self.loss_history)),
            'Loss': self.loss_history
        }), x='Step', y='Loss', ax=ax2, color='red')
        ax2.set_title('Loss Over Steps', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Q-value
        ax3 = fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 0])  # Third row, first column
        sns.lineplot(data=pd.DataFrame({
            'Step': range(len(self.q_value_history)),
            'Q-value': self.q_value_history
        }), x='Step', y='Q-value', ax=ax3, color='green')
        ax3.set_title('Q-value Over Steps', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Standard Deviation of Rewards
        ax4 = fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 1])  # Third row, second column
        sns.lineplot(data=pd.DataFrame({
            'Episode': range(len(self.sd_history)),
            'Standard Deviation': self.sd_history
        }), x='Episode', y='Standard Deviation', ax=ax4, color='orange')
        ax4.set_title('Standard Deviation of Rewards', fontsize=16)

        plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])  # Adjust layout to fit everything
        plt.show()

    def add_noise(self, action):
        noise = np.random.normal(0, self.noise_std, size=action.shape)
        return action + noise
In [ ]:
env = gym.make("Pendulum-v0")
finalModel = ImprovedDDPG(Gamma=best_gamma,
            BatchSize=best_batch_size,
            IntermediateSize=best_intermediate_size)
finalModel.ActorOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=best_lr)
finalModel.CriticOptimizer = Adam(learning_rate=best_lr)

n_episodes = 150
returns = []
for episode in range(n_episodes):
    print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
    one_episode(finalModel, env)
    if len(finalModel.return_history) > 0:
        returns.append(finalModel.return_history[-1])

create_ddpg_gif(finalModel)
finalModel.plot_magnitudes()
plt.show()

avg_return = sum(returns) / len(returns) if returns else 0

Observation

  • Exploration vs. Exploitation: The application of OU noise seems effective in promoting exploration, as indicated by the variance in rewards and the relatively stable yet non-improving episode returns. However, the high and stable loss alongside non-improving returns suggests possible issues in exploiting learned knowledge to achieve better outcomes.
  • Gradient Over Steps: The gradient values start high and then decrease over time, a typical pattern indicating the agent is learning and adjusting its parameters.
  • Loss Over Steps: The loss remains relatively high and does not show a clear decreasing trend, which could imply challenges in learning optimal actions.
  • Q-value Over Steps: The plateau in episode returns alongside increasing Q-values suggests that while the agent is valuing future states more optimistically, it is not translating this into better policy performance.
  • Standard Deviation of Rewards: High variability, instability or inconsistency in the policy performance across different states of the environment.

Grid Search on DQN¶

DDPG doesn't seem to be improving even after hypertuning & improving architecture!!!
We will now do a grid search on the most promising model (Baseline) as it has a steady learning curve.

In [ ]:
def OneEpisode(agent):
    env = gym.make(f'{EnvName}')
    S = env.reset()
    ListOfRewards = []
    Done = False
    step_count = 0
    
    while not Done:
        Q = agent.Main(S.reshape(-1, S.shape[0]))
        if np.random.rand() < Epsilon:
            AStep = env.action_space.sample()
            A = PendulumInverseActionConverter(AStep[0])
        else:
            A = np.argmax(Q)
            A = PendulumActionConverter(A)
            AStep = np.array([A])
            A = PendulumInverseActionConverter(A)
        
        SNext, R, Done, Info = env.step(AStep)
        agent.UpdateReplayMemory((S, A, R, SNext, Done))
        agent.Train(Done)
        ListOfRewards.append(R)
        S = SNext
        step_count += 1
    
    total_reward = np.sum(ListOfRewards)
    agent.return_history.append(total_reward)
    agent.sd_history.append(np.std(ListOfRewards))
    print(f'Finished! Return: {total_reward}')
    env.close()
    return total_reward

class HypertuneBaseline:
    def __init__(self,
                 InputShape = 3,
                 NActions = 2,
                 Gamma = 1,
                 ReplayMemorySize = 10000,
                 MinReplayMemory = 1000,
                 UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes = 1,
                 IntermediateSize = 64,
                 BatchSize = 32):
        self.name = 'FinalModel'
        self.avg_return = 0
        
        # Hyperparameters. #
        self.InputShape = InputShape
        self.NActions = NActions
        self.Gamma = Gamma
        self.ReplayMemorySize = ReplayMemorySize
        self.MinReplayMemory = MinReplayMemory
        self.UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes = UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes
        self.IntermediateSize = IntermediateSize
        self.BatchSize = BatchSize
        self.return_history = []
        self.loss_history = []
        self.q_value_history = []
        self.gradient_history = []
        self.sd_history = []

        # Main model. #
        self.Main = self.CreateModel('Main')
        self.Optimiser = Adam()
        
        # Target model. #
        self.Target = self.CreateModel('Target')
        self.Target.set_weights(self.Main.get_weights())
        
        # Replay memory. #
        self.ReplayMemory = deque(maxlen = ReplayMemorySize)
        
        # Target network update counter. #
        self.TargetUpdateCounter = 0
    
    def plot_magnitudes(self):
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 12))  # Set the figure size
        gs = GridSpec(3, 2)  # Define a grid with 3 rows and 2 columns

        # Create the top subplot for Episode Return
        ax_top = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, :])  # Span all columns of the first row
        return_df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Episode': range(len(self.return_history)),
            'Return': self.return_history
        })
        sns.lineplot(data=return_df, x='Episode', y='Return', ax=ax_top)
        ax_top.set_title('Episode Return Over Time', fontsize=16)

        # Create subplots for the rest
        # Plot Gradient
        ax1 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 0])  # Second row, first column
        sns.lineplot(data=pd.DataFrame({
            'Step': range(len(self.gradient_history)),
            'Gradient': self.gradient_history
        }), x='Step', y='Gradient', ax=ax1, color='blue')
        ax1.set_title('Gradient Over Steps', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Loss
        ax2 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 1])  # Second row, second column
        sns.lineplot(data=pd.DataFrame({
            'Step': range(len(self.loss_history)),
            'Loss': self.loss_history
        }), x='Step', y='Loss', ax=ax2, color='red')
        ax2.set_title('Loss Over Steps', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Q-value
        ax3 = fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 0])  # Third row, first column
        sns.lineplot(data=pd.DataFrame({
            'Step': range(len(self.q_value_history)),
            'Q-value': self.q_value_history
        }), x='Step', y='Q-value', ax=ax3, color='green')
        ax3.set_title('Q-value Over Steps', fontsize=16)

        # Plot Standard Deviation of Rewards
        ax4 = fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 1])  # Third row, second column
        sns.lineplot(data=pd.DataFrame({
            'Episode': range(len(self.sd_history)),
            'Standard Deviation': self.sd_history
        }), x='Episode', y='Standard Deviation', ax=ax4, color='orange')
        ax4.set_title('Standard Deviation of Rewards', fontsize=16)

        plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])  # Adjust layout to fit everything
        plt.show()
            
    def CreateModel(self, Type):
        inputs = Input(shape = (self.InputShape), name = 'Input')
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation = 'relu', name = '1stHiddenLayer')(inputs)
        x = Dense(self.IntermediateSize, activation = 'relu', name = '2ndHiddenLayer')(x)
        outputs = Dense(self.NActions, activation = 'linear', name = 'Output')(x)
        
        NN = Model(inputs, outputs, name = f'{Type}')
        NN.summary()
        
        return NN
    
    def UpdateReplayMemory(self, Information): # Information = (S, A, R, SNext, Done)
        self.ReplayMemory.append(Information)

    def Train(self, EndOfEpisode):
        if len(self.ReplayMemory) < self.MinReplayMemory:
            return
        
        # Get batch of data for training. #
        TrainingData = random.sample(self.ReplayMemory, self.BatchSize)
        
        # Get states from training data, then get corresponding Q values. #
        ListOfS = np.array([element[0] for element in TrainingData])
        ListOfQ = np.array(self.Main(ListOfS))
        
        # Get future states from training data, then get corresponding Q values. #
        ListOfSNext = np.array([element[3] for element in TrainingData])
        ListOfQNext = self.Target(ListOfSNext)
        
        # Build actual training data for neural network. #
        X = []
        Y = []
        for index, (S, A, R, SNext, Done) in enumerate(TrainingData):
            if not Done:
                MaxQNext = np.max(ListOfQNext[index])
                QNext = R + self.Gamma * MaxQNext
            else:
                QNext = R
            Q = ListOfQ[index]
            Q[A] = QNext
        
            X.append(S)
            Y.append(Q)
        
        # Train model using tf.GradientTape(), defined below.
        Loss, Predictions, Grad = self.GTfit(X, Y)
        self.loss_history.append(float(Loss))
        self.q_value_history.append(float(tf.reduce_mean(Predictions)))
        self.gradient_history.append(float(tf.linalg.global_norm(Grad)))
                
        # Update target network every episode. #
        if EndOfEpisode:
            self.TargetUpdateCounter += 1
        
        # Update target if counter is full. #
        if self.TargetUpdateCounter >= self.UpdateTargetEveryThisEpisodes:
            self.Target.set_weights(self.Main.get_weights())
            self.TargetUpdateCounter = 0
    
    @tf.function
    def GTfit(self, X, Y):
        with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
            Predictions = self.Main(tf.convert_to_tensor(X), training=True)
            Loss = tf.math.reduce_mean(tf.math.square(tf.convert_to_tensor(Y) - Predictions))
        Grad = tape.gradient(Loss, self.Main.trainable_variables)
        self.Optimiser.apply_gradients(zip(Grad, self.Main.trainable_variables))
        return Loss, Predictions, Grad
In [ ]:
HyperParams = namedtuple('HyperParams', [
    'intermediate_size', 
    'learning_rate', 
    'gamma', 
    'batch_size'
])

# Define the hyperparameter search space
param_dist = {
    'intermediate_size': [32, 64],
    'learning_rate': [0.0001, 0.001],
    'gamma': [0.9, 0.95],
    'batch_size': [32, 64]
}

def grid_search_params(param_dist):
    keys, values = zip(*param_dist.items())
    for v in itertools.product(*values):
        yield HyperParams(**dict(zip(keys, v)))

def run_experiment(params, n_episodes=100, finalFlag=False):
    finalModel = HypertuneBaseline(
        InputShape=InputShape, 
        NActions=NActions,
        IntermediateSize=params.intermediate_size,
        Gamma=params.gamma,
        BatchSize=params.batch_size
    )
    
    finalModel.Optimiser = Adam(learning_rate=params.learning_rate)
    
    returns = []
    for episode in range(n_episodes):
        if episode % ShowEvery == 0:
            print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
            
        result = OneEpisode(finalModel)
        if isinstance(result, dict):
            # If OneEpisode returns a dict, we'll assume it contains the return
            returns.append(result.get('return', 0))
        elif len(finalModel.return_history) > 0:
            returns.append(finalModel.return_history[-1])

    if finalFlag:
        create_gif(finalModel)
        finalModel.plot_magnitudes()
        plt.show()
    
    avg_return = np.mean(returns) if returns else 0
    finalModel.avg_return = avg_return
    return avg_return

best_params = None
best_avg_return = float('-inf')

for params in grid_search_params(param_dist):
    print(f"\nTrying configuration:")
    print(f"Params: {params}")
    
    avg_return = run_experiment(params)
    print(f"Average return: {avg_return:.2f}")
    
    if avg_return > best_avg_return:
        best_avg_return = avg_return
        best_params = params

print("\nBest hyperparameters found:")
print(f"Params: {best_params}")
print(f"Best average return: {best_avg_return:.2f}")

# Run a final experiment with the best parameters
print("\nRunning final experiment with best parameters...")
final_avg_return = run_experiment(best_params, finalFlag=True)
print(f"Final average return: {final_avg_return:.2f}")

Re-Running¶

Number of trial is also a criteria.
In Reinforcement Learning, we don't get the same results everytime, there is still that randomness.
Hence, lets re-train the model to see if its a fluke.


In [ ]:
finalModel = HypertuneBaseline(
        InputShape=InputShape, 
        NActions=NActions,
        IntermediateSize=64,
        Gamma=0.95,
        BatchSize=64
    )

finalModel.Optimiser = Adam(learning_rate=0.001)

returns = []
for episode in range(n_episodes):
    if episode % ShowEvery == 0:
        print(f'Episode {episode}', end=' ')
        
    result = OneEpisode(finalModel)
    if isinstance(result, dict):
        # If OneEpisode returns a dict, we'll assume it contains the return
        returns.append(result.get('return', 0))
    elif len(finalModel.return_history) > 0:
        returns.append(finalModel.return_history[-1])

create_gif(finalModel)
finalModel.plot_magnitudes()
finalModel.Main.save('./CA2-Model/RL/FinalModel.h5')
plt.show()

Observation

  • Model has a steady increase in rewards. until it stablized at -250 after the 80th episode
  • Loss & Gradient shows a rise then fall, which shows that it explored and changing the model (Stopped learning after 24000 steps).
  • The standard deviation of rewards remains fairly high throughout the episodes but shows a slight downwards trend.
  • Q-values initially decreased then increased, stabilizing later in the training. Agent begins with overestimations of expected rewards, which corrects and converge to more realistic values as training progresses.

Save & Load Weights¶

In [ ]:
def visualiseOneEpisode(agent):
    env = gym.make(f'{EnvName}')
    S = env.reset()
    ListOfRewards = []
    Done = False
    step_count = 0
    
    while not Done:
        Q = agent.Main(S.reshape(-1, S.shape[0]))
        if np.random.rand() < Epsilon:
            AStep = env.action_space.sample()
            A = PendulumInverseActionConverter(AStep[0])
        else:
            A = np.argmax(Q)
            A = PendulumActionConverter(A)
            AStep = np.array([A])
            A = PendulumInverseActionConverter(A)
        env.render()
        SNext, R, Done, Info = env.step(AStep)
        agent.UpdateReplayMemory((S, A, R, SNext, Done))
        agent.Train(Done)
        ListOfRewards.append(R)
        S = SNext
        step_count += 1
    
    total_reward = np.sum(ListOfRewards)
    agent.return_history.append(total_reward)
    agent.sd_history.append(np.std(ListOfRewards))
    print(f'Finished! Return: {total_reward}')
    env.close()
    return total_reward

agent = HypertuneBaseline()
agent.Main = tf.keras.models.load_model("./CA2-Model/RL/FinalModel.h5")

Conclusion¶

Our Environment is a continuous evironment. Which is why we use architectures like DDPG. However, the models all seem to be exploiting then exploring even after trying to improve it.

Hence, we found the best DQN, which seems to be learning. But it also explores more than it exploits which is due to its architecture being best for discrete actions. Therefore, it seems like its unstable.

It also could be because of the chance of initial spawn of the environment that may cause it to have 'bad' returns.

Final Questions¶

  • Systematically optimize your solutions:

    • Implement a structured approach such as grid search & random search to explore the hyperparameter space.
    • For models that lacked exploration, we change the architecture, Such as NoisyDQN or OUNoise to the model to increase exploration.

  • What hyperparameters can you tune?:

    • Learning Rate
    • Gamma (Discount Factor)
    • Batch Size
    • Intermediate Size

    Those were the most critical factors that had the most affect to our model.

  • How many trials does it need?:

    • We rerun it a second time to try to reduce the randomness of the environment.
    • Our best models took around 80 episodes to fully learn the environment and stop improving.
    • The other architectures didn't seem to be improving at all.

  • How do you conclusively demonstrate your so-called “best setup” to be the best?:

    • By looking at the different magnitudes
      • Loss
      • Gradient
      • Q-value
      • Standard Deviation

  • What is criteria to use (fastest learning | most stable learning)?:

    • Fastest Learning: By looking at its Gradient Magnitude we can see exactly where its modifying itself and when its not
    • Most Stable Learning: Choose settings that produce the least variance in performance across multiple runs.
